o ideas, individuals, and groups now at the forefront of the fight against rational immigration policies. Not Fit for Our Society makes a powerful case for understanding the complex, often paradoxical history of immigration restriction as we work through the issues that inform, and often distort, the debate over who can become a citizen, who decides, and on what basis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEmigration and immigrationxGovernment policy. 0aEmigration and immigrationxPublic opinion. 0aEmigration and immigrationxSocial aspects. 0aEugenics. 0aNativism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh  aamerica.  aamerican citizenship.  aamerican culture.  aamerican history.  aamerican society.  achinese immigrants.  acontroversial.  acurrent events.  adiscussion books.  afear and change.  agerman immigrants.  ahistorical nonfiction.  aimmigrants.  aimmigration debate.  aimmigration policies.  aimmigration.  airish immigrants.  aitalian immigrants.  ajewish immigrants.  alatino immigrants.  amodern immigration.  anativism.  apolitical issues.  apolitics.  arace and immigration.  asocial change.  astudents and teachers.  aunited states.  aus history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025978240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094577740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520945777423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520945777/original  a978-3-11-063872-1  DG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_Y